MCP server tool (screenshot-tab.ts):
- Zod input: z.object({ tabId: z.number().int().positive().describe('Tab ID to screenshot — the tab will be focused automatically before capture') })
- Description: 'Capture a screenshot of the visible area of a browser tab as a base64-encoded PNG image. The tab is automatically focused before capture. Returns the image as a base64 string without the data URI prefix.'
- Dispatch: dispatchToExtension(state, 'browser.screenshotTab', { tabId: args.tabId })

Extension handler (browser-commands.ts):
- handleBrowserScreenshotTab(params, id):
  1. Validate tabId is a number
  2. const tab = await chrome.tabs.update(tabId, { active: true });
  3. await chrome.windows.update(tab.windowId, { focused: true });
  4. Small delay (100ms) for the tab to render after focus
  5. const dataUrl = await chrome.tabs.captureVisibleTab(tab.windowId, { format: 'png' });
  6. const base64 = dataUrl.replace(/^data:image\/png;base64,/, '');
  7. sendToServer({ jsonrpc: '2.0', result: { image: base64 }, id });

Note: captureVisibleTab captures the ACTIVE tab in the given window. That's why we focus the tab first. The 100ms delay helps ensure the tab's content is rendered.

All three tools follow the same pattern: MCP server tool dispatches to extension, extension uses chrome.scripting.executeScript with { func, args }.

click-element.ts:
- Input: { tabId: z.number().int().positive(), selector: z.string().min(1).describe('CSS selector of the element to click (e.g., "button#submit", ".nav-link")') }
- Description: 'Click an element on the page matching the given CSS selector. Dispatches a click event on the first matching element. Returns the tag name and trimmed text content of the clicked element. Useful for submitting forms, toggling buttons, and navigating.'
- Extension func: querySelector(sel), if !el return { error }, el.click(), return { clicked: true, tagName: el.tagName.toLowerCase(), text: (el.textContent || '').trim().slice(0, 200) }

type-text.ts:
- Input: { tabId, selector: z.string().min(1).describe('CSS selector of the input or textarea'), text: z.string().describe('Text to enter into the element'), clear: z.boolean().optional().describe('Clear existing value before typing — defaults to true') }
- Description: 'Type text into an input field or textarea matching the CSS selector. Focuses the element, optionally clears existing content, sets the value, and dispatches input and change events to trigger any attached event listeners.'
- Extension func: querySelector(sel), el.focus(), if (clear !== false) el.value = '', el.value = text (or el.value += text if clear=false), el.dispatchEvent(new Event('input', { bubbles: true })), el.dispatchEvent(new Event('change', { bubbles: true })), return { typed: true, tagName, value: el.value }

select-option.ts:
- Input: { tabId, selector: z.string().min(1).describe('CSS selector of the <select> element'), value: z.string().optional().describe('Option value attribute to select'), label: z.string().optional().describe('Option visible text to select — used when value is not provided') }
- Description: 'Select an option from a <select> dropdown element by option value or visible label text. Dispatches a change event after selection. Specify either value or label — value takes precedence if both provided.'
- Extension func: find select, iterate options to find by value or textContent, set selectedIndex, dispatch change event, return { selected: true, value, label }

Message router entries follow the exact pattern of existing browser.* handlers.

wait-for-element.ts:
- Input: { tabId, selector: z.string().min(1).describe('CSS selector to wait for'), timeout: z.number().int().positive().optional().describe('Max wait time in ms — defaults to 10000'), visible: z.boolean().optional().describe('Also require element to be visible, not display:none or visibility:hidden — defaults to false') }
- Description: 'Wait for an element matching the CSS selector to appear in the DOM. Polls the page until the element is found or timeout expires. For SPAs where content loads asynchronously. Set visible=true to also require the element to be visible (not hidden by CSS).'
- Extension handler: The executeScript func runs a polling loop using Promise + setInterval. Inside the func: return new Promise((resolve) => { let elapsed = 0; const poll = setInterval(() => { const el = document.querySelector(sel); if (el && (!vis || (el.offsetParent !== null || getComputedStyle(el).display !== 'none'))) { clearInterval(poll); resolve({ found: true, tagName, text }); } elapsed += 100; if (elapsed >= timeout) { clearInterval(poll); resolve({ error: 'Timeout' }); } }, 100); });
- The extension handler must handle the async result (the Promise resolves to the result object).

query-elements.ts:
- Input: { tabId, selector: z.string().min(1).describe('CSS selector to query'), limit: z.number().int().positive().optional().describe('Max elements to return — defaults to 100'), attributes: z.array(z.string()).optional().describe('Attribute names to extract — defaults to id, class, href, src, type, name, value, placeholder') }
- Description: 'Query all elements matching a CSS selector and return their tag names, trimmed text content (first 200 chars), and specified HTML attributes. Useful for understanding page structure, finding interactive elements, and inspecting forms. Returns up to limit elements.'
- Extension func: querySelectorAll(sel), slice(0, limit), map each to { tagName, text: (el.textContent||'').trim().slice(0,200), attributes: Object.fromEntries(attrs.filter(a => el.hasAttribute(a)).map(a => [a, el.getAttribute(a)])) }, return { count: all.length, elements }

For wait_for_element, the chrome.scripting.executeScript result will be a Promise that Chrome automatically awaits.

This story creates the extension-side state management that the network capture and console log MCP tools will dispatch to. The MCP tools themselves are in US-009 and US-010.

File: platform/browser-extension/src/network-capture.ts

Key design:
```typescript
interface CapturedRequest {
  url: string;
  method: string;
  status?: number;
  statusText?: string;
  requestHeaders?: Record<string, string>;
  responseHeaders?: Record<string, string>;
  mimeType?: string;
  timestamp: number;
}

interface ConsoleEntry {
  level: string; // 'log' | 'warn' | 'error' | 'info' | 'debug'
  message: string;
  timestamp: number;
}

interface CaptureState {
  requests: CapturedRequest[];
  consoleLogs: ConsoleEntry[];
  maxRequests: number;
  urlFilter?: string;
  pendingRequests: Map<string, Partial<CapturedRequest>>; // requestId -> partial
}

const captures = new Map<number, CaptureState>();
```

chrome.debugger.onEvent.addListener((source, method, params) => {
  const tabId = source.tabId;
  const state = captures.get(tabId);
  if (!state) return;
  // Handle Network.requestWillBeSent: create pending request
  // Handle Network.responseReceived: merge response data into pending request, move to requests buffer
  // Handle Runtime.consoleAPICalled: add to consoleLogs buffer
});

chrome.tabs.onRemoved.addListener(tabId => {
  if (captures.has(tabId)) {
    try { chrome.debugger.detach({ tabId }); } catch {}
    captures.delete(tabId);
  }
});

Important: chrome.debugger.attach may fail if another debugger is already attached (e.g., DevTools). Handle this gracefully with an error message.

The onEvent listener should be registered once at module load time, not per-tab. It routes events to the correct tab's state via source.tabId.

